<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-795-332  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 795 332.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 27 1990 v24 n35 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Decisions, decisions. (IBM's marketing strategy; Commentary)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM has been and still is confusing its customers with its arrayof mid-range processor families that overlap in price-performanceand functionality.andP;  What users would really like to see is asingle platform capable of connecting different local-areanetworks (LANs) to various communications environments.andP;  Whatwould be especially nice is an upgradable platform that functionsas a network file- and disk-server, Netview service point androuter/gateway.andP;  That ideal platform would boast a reasonableentry price, support IBM's low-end networking, connect directly toeither a Token-Ring or Ethernet LAN, and route transmissions overa T1 or Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) link to a hostor other resource.andP;  IBM has made a statement of directionpromising to implement some of these ideas in some of itsproducts.andP;  However, which platform will arise as the 'GreatCommunicator?'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     InteroperabilityLocal Area NetworksUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>